Chapter Twenty Six

+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| 重 為 輕 根                       | Serious serves as the source of   |
|                                   | frivolous.                        |
| 靜 為 躁 君                       | Stillness serves as the ruler of  |
|                                   | restlessness.                     |
| 是 以 (君 子) 終 日               |                                   |
|                                   | Thus the noble man travels the    |
| 行 不 離 [其] 輜                  | entire day,                       |
|                                   |                                   |
| 重 雖 有 榮 觀 燕                 | And does not stray from his       |
|                                   | wagon.                            |
| 處 超 然                          |                                   |
|                                   | He is serious, even though        |
| 奈 何 萬 乘 之 主                 | glorious sights and feasts exist; |
|                                   |                                   |
| 而 以 身 輕 天 下                 | He lives above them, like this.   |
|                                   |                                   |
| 輕 則 失 本                       | So how could one be the master of |
|                                   | ten thousand chariots,            |
| 躁 則 失 君                       |                                   |
|                                   | And conduct his self frivolously  |
|                                   | in the world?                     |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Be frivolous, then lose the       |
|                                   | source.                           |
|                                   | Be restless, then lose the        |
|                                   | rulership.                        |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| ♦Serious{heavy} serves as the     | Notes                             |
| source of frivolous{light}.       |                                   |
| ♦Stillness serves as the ruler of | A : this symbol also means        |
| restlessness^(A).                 | impatience, agitation, anxiety,   |
| Thus² the noble man²*^(B) travels | etc; “stillness” and              |
| the entire day,                   | “restlessness” are presumably     |
|                                   | referring to inner,               |
| And does not stray from his       | mental/emotional qualities        |
| wagon.  [leave,depart,separate]   |                                   |
|                                   | B : Only WB and HSG changed       |
| He is serious^(C), even though    | “noble man” to the non-Confucian  |
| glorious sights and feasts exist; | term “sage”                       |
|                                   |                                   |
| He lives above them, like         | C : traditionally, the first      |
| this^(D).                         | symbol of this sentence is        |
| [transcend,jump over]             | considered to be the last symbol  |
| [So] how² could [one be] the      | of the previous sentence (“heavy  |
| master of ten thousand            | wagon”); but because the MWD’s    |
|                                   | have “fields” instead of “wagon”  |
|       chariots,^(E)               | at the end of the previous        |
|                                   | sentence, and “heavy fields”      |
| And conduct his self ^(F)         | makes no sense, it is parsed this |
| frivolously{lightly} in the       | way                               |
| world²?                           |                                   |
|                                   | D : presumably, by being serious  |
|                                   | and still                         |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | E : someone very important, such  |
|          [use]                    | as the supreme ruler of a large   |
|                                   | nation (one with 10,000 chariots) |
| Be frivolous{light}, then lose    |                                   |
| the source.                       | F : this is written in this       |
| ♦Be restless, then lose the       | awkward manner to emphasize that  |
| rulership.                        | it is the personality or          |
|                                   | sense-of-self that is being       |
|                                   | talked about (in the translator’s |
|                                   | opinion – see the Introduction    |
|                                   | and cross-references below)       |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
