Chapter Thirty Eight

+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| 上 德 不 德 是 以 有 德           | A man of highest De does not use  |
|                                   | his De, thus he                   |
| 下 德 不 失 德 是 以 無 德        |                                   |
|                                   |       possesses De.               |
| 上 德 無 為 而 無 以 為 •         |                                   |
|                                   | A man of inferior De does not     |
| 下 德 為 之 而 有 以 為           | lose his De, thus he is           |
|                                   |                                   |
| 上 仁 為 之 而 無 以 為 •         |       without De.                 |
|                                   |                                   |
| 上 義 為 之 而 有 以 為 •         |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
| 上 禮 為 之 而 莫 之 以 應 •      | A man of highest De uses          |
|                                   | non-action, and acts without      |
| 則 攘 臂 而 (仍) 之               |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
| (•)故 失 道 而 後 德              | mot                               |
|                                   | ive.                              |
| 失 德 而 後 仁                    |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
| 失 仁 而 後 義 •                  | A man of inferior De coerces      |
|                                   | others, and has a motive to       |
| 失 義 而 後 禮                    |                                   |
|                                   |       act.                        |
| (•)夫 禮 者 忠 信 之 薄 •         |                                   |
|                                   | A man of highest kindness coerces |
| 而 亂 之 首 •                     | others, and acts                  |
|                                   |                                   |
| 前 識 者 道 之 華 •               |       without motive.             |
|                                   |                                   |
| 而 愚 之 始 •                     | A man of highest morality coerces |
|                                   | others, and has a                 |
| 是 以 大 丈 夫                    |                                   |
|                                   |       motive to act.              |
| 處 其 厚 不 居 其 薄              |                                   |
|                                   | A man of highest propriety        |
| 處 其 實 不 居 其 華              | coerces others, and if there      |
|                                   |                                   |
| (•)故 去 彼 取 此 •               |       is no one who responds,     |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Then he rolls up his sleeves and  |
|                                   | keeps doing it.                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Therefore : lose Dao, and later   |
|                                   | comes De.                         |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Lose De, and later comes          |
|                                   | kindness.                         |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Lose kindness, and later comes    |
|                                   | morality.                         |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Lose morality, and later comes    |
|                                   | propriety.                        |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | Now : propriety is that which is  |
|                                   | merely the appearance of          |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |       loyalty and honesty,        |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | And the beginning of confusion.   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   |                                   |
