| Yin and embrace Yang,             | but in keeping with other         |
|                                   | chapters, this is interpreted     |
| ♦Pouring their Qi together, thus  | more generally as “nobles”        |
| becoming harmonious.              |                                   |
|                                   | D : 教 父 is often translated as  |
| ♦That which people [they] detest  | some variant of “senior teaching” |
| :                                 | (primary teaching, essence of     |
|                                   | teaching, principal teaching,     |
| ♦Being alone, orphaned{lonely},   | etc.), but it also means          |
| lonely{widowed}, and              | “godfather” in the best sense of  |
|                                   | the term (friend and teacher),    |
|       unlucky^(2B) –              | and this translation is           |
|                                   | consistent with #27, where a      |
