| ♦When your courage* lies in       | Notes                             |
| daring,                           |                                   |
|                                   | There are two themes in this      |
| ♦The consequence is killing.      | chapter which do not seem to fit  |
|                                   | in with typical Daoist concepts – |
| ♦When your courage* lies in not   | that of heaven conquering         |
| daring,                           | (literally “victory” or “beat”,   |
|                                   | interpreted as “achieving its     |
| ♦The consequence is survival.     | goals”) which sounds more like    |
|                                   | striving than non-action, and     |
| ♦These two [choices], they        | planning (interpreted as          |
| sometimes cause benefit,          | “prepares”) which seems           |
|                                   | contradictory to being “naturally |
|       sometimes cause harm.       | so” (although the sage also       |
|                                   | “plans” here and in #63)          |
|                                   |                                   |
|                                   | A : in early societies, whatever  |
|   [maybe,perhaps] [maybe,perhaps] | endeavors failed were by          |
|                                   | definition what heaven (or the    |
| ♦That which heaven [it]           | gods) “detested”                  |
| detests^(A) – who knows its       |                                   |
| reasons?                          | B : this sentence only appears in |
|                                   | the later sources, and seems to   |
| Thus² the sage² plans for things  | be a parenthetical comment;       |
| to be difficult.^(B)              | although it technically is in the |
|                                   | majority, it seems so             |
|                                   | out-of-place that it is left out  |
|                [them] [schemes]   | of the final translation above    |
|                                   |                                   |
| ♦The Way of heaven :              | C : this sentence is nearly       |
|                                   | impossible to translate; while    |
| ♦Does not strive, yet skillfully  | the first symbol in WB and HSG    |
| achieves its goals.               | are the same, making them the     |
|                                   | default “majority”, it is         |
|                                   | different in every other source,  |
|         [victory,beat]            | and none of their modern          |
|                                   | translations make sense; some     |
| ♦Does not speak, yet skillfully   | translators use a symbol slightly |
| responds.                         | different than that in WB and HSG |
|                                   | but pronounced the same way;      |
| ♦Does not summon, yet everything  | finally, “slow, patient, calm” is |
| naturally comes to it.            | only the most likely translation  |
|                                   | that could be found for the first |
| Is certainly unhurried, yet       | symbol                            |
| skillfully                        |                                   |
| prepares.^(C)                     | D : “extremely” is implied by the |
|                                   | repeated symbol                   |
|                                   |                                   |
|             [slow,patient,calm]   |                                   |
| [plans]                           |                                   |
